<TITLE> UN prosecutor urges EU to stay tough with Serbia </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, Dec 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The chief UN war crimes prosecutor for the former Yugoslavia urged the European Union on Tuesday to stand firm and not sign an accord on closer ties with Serbia until Belgrade hands over a key genocide indictee. Carla del Ponte told reporters after visiting Belgrade on Monday that the EU's pending signature of a Stabilisation and Association Agreement, the first rung on the ladder to membership, gave her the strongest leverage to obtain the arrest of former Bosnian Serb military commander Ratko Mladic. "The European Union should stand firm: no signature without the fugitives in The Hague, in particular Mladic," the outgoing prosecutor said. "If we lose this leverage, we will never get that." Del Ponte told a Balkans conference at the Friends of Europe think-tank she believed Serbia now wanted to cooperate with the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia (ICTY) although it still had to deliver results. "It is extremely important that the European Union is helping us obtain this cooperation," she said. All evidence collected by the Serbian authorities proved that Mladic was in the country, but he enjoyed protection from people affiliated with the ultra-nationalist Radical Party of fellow war crimes indictee Vojislav Seselj. "I know that they can do (it) but I really don't know if it is only a technical problem to locate him in time, because he is still protected a lot as you know from the Radicals, or if they are waiting till the last moment to deliver him," she said. Del Ponte implicitly rebuffed a call by Serbian Deputy Prime Minister Bozidar Delic for the EU to speed up Belgrade's accession process to give a boost to democratic forces and prevent nationalists regaining power. Pointing to a Serbian presidential election set for Jan. 20 and Feb. 13, Delic told the conference: "It is of the highest importance for Serbia and Europe for there to be, as we have now, a pro-European President (Boris) Tadic... "It'